## §7 — Five Piece-Angle Ideas (Ranked by Editor Appeal)

Ranked from highest to lowest editor appeal based on: empirical grounding available now, novelty of claim, fit across the outlet rotation, and load-bearing receipts already in vault.

---

### Rank 1 — "Free AI Beats Paid Flagships on Accuracy, Privacy, and Cost: Here Is the Proof"

**Thesis:** A free, locally-run open-source model augmented with a cooperative substrate outperforms four paid flagship models (Opus, GPT-4o, Gemini 2.5 Pro, Llama 3.1 405B) on MMLU-Pro accuracy, at zero ongoing API cost, with full data privacy.

**Primary outlet target:** Wired (first), The Verge (second if Wired passes)

**Load-bearing proof receipt:** BP078_TIER3_EMPIRICAL_BENCHMARK_PLAN.md + BP078_TIER3_GEMMA4_VS_FLAGSHIPS_RECEIPT.eblet.md (gate: receipt must exist before piece fires)

**Editor appeal notes:** This is a product story with a concrete benchmark. Wired and The Verge cover this beat. "Free beats paid" is the headline. The privacy angle (data stays on your computer, zero API cost) is a secondary hook that broadens to non-technical readers.

**Gate:** Tier 3 benchmark receipt must exist. Do not write this piece as if the results are known. Write it after the receipt is stamped.

---

### Rank 2 — "The Cooperative AI Model: 83.3% Creator Keep, Cost+20%, No VC Required"

**Thesis:** There is a third architecture for AI infrastructure: cooperative, not corporate. Creators keep 83.3% of value. Pricing is Cost+20%. Governance is member-owned. This is not charity and it is not a startup — it is a cooperative with 21 provisional patents protecting the commons.

**Primary outlet target:** The Atlantic (first), Bloomberg Opinion (second if Atlantic passes)

**Load-bearing proof receipt:** BP067 close-stamp (83.3% canon, pearl_0b38f599) + BP069 close-stamp (20% gain-share ratified, pearl_71edf0c5) + SUBSTACK_CONSIDERED_APPROACH_BP072.md (near-ready draft)

**Editor appeal notes:** Atlantic and Bloomberg Opinion want the economic argument. This is the "third architecture" framing that the NYT op-ed used — but now anchored to live canons, not a pitch. The MacKenzie Scott letter (SUBSTACK_CARDBOARD_BOOTS_MACKENZIE_BP072.md) has overlapping prose that can be repurposed.

**Gate:** Counsel review on the CDPP and gain-share sections before public publish (BP077 close-stamp notes counsel settled — confirm this covers the published essay framing).

---

### Rank 3 — "The Memory-Wall Cure: How AI Agents Stopped Repeating Themselves"

**Thesis:** AI agents forget everything between sessions. We built a session-close ingest gate and a persistent substrate so agents never repeat work. The cure is not a language model improvement — it is a cooperative substrate discipline. 38 lost load-bearing items recovered in the pilot. This is what "never repeat work again" looks like in practice.

**Primary outlet target:** MIT Technology Review (first), Wired (second if MIT Tech passes)

**Load-bearing proof receipt:** BP070 close-stamp (gate now + pilot backfill, ~38 lost items recovered, Memory-Wall Cure canon) + canon_bp078_plow_first_then_test_then_replow_spider_sprite_miner_design_bp078

**Editor appeal notes:** MIT Tech Review publishes deep architectural pieces. The Memory-Wall Cure is a novel framing of a real problem (context window loss, session boundary fragmentation) with a documented empirical fix. The plow-first architecture proof from BP078 Phase A (1342 eblets, 8858.7s wall clock) is the concrete receipt.

**Gate:** Requires honest framing — the gate is "never repeat work" for the substrate layer, not for the LLM layer. Do not overclaim into general AI memory.

---

### Rank 4 — "Show HN: MnemosyneC — Free, Offline, Cooperative AI That Remembers Your Work"

**Thesis:** We built a local AI with a cooperative substrate that compounds knowledge across sessions. Free forever. No ads. Data stays on your computer. We are open for membership at $5/yr.

**Primary outlet target:** Hacker News Show HN (first)

**Load-bearing proof receipt:** v0.1.27 NANO SHA-256 (58A9FFC7...) + BP078 close-stamp v0.1.27 ship confirmed + mesh proof pearl_88a8c069 (20/20 hash-verified, two physical machines)

**Editor appeal notes:** This is not an op-ed — it is a Show HN post. Short. Working demo link. SHA hash. HN community will probe the technical claims, so the receipt chain must be airtight. Do not overreach beyond what is shipped and verifiable.

**Gate:** Wave 0 gate per BP075 must be met — v0.1.27 working, lianabanyan.com live, /proofs clean, $5/yr Stripe live.

---

### Rank 5 — "Truth-Always: How We Caught Our Own Overclaims Before They Went Public"

**Thesis:** We built a verify-net inside our development process that caught four overclaims in BP067, two in BP069, and three in BP078 before they shipped. This is not a story about AI accuracy — it is a story about accountability discipline and why cooperative software needs it more than corporate software.

**Primary outlet target:** ProPublica (first), The Atlantic (second if ProPublica passes)

**Load-bearing proof receipt:** BP067 close-stamp (verify-net caught 3 overclaims), BP069 close-stamp (DIRTY DOZEN 8/12 verified, gate-NOT-met, overclaim caught), BP078 close-stamp (4 verify-net catches listed in ss7)

**Editor appeal notes:** ProPublica publishes investigative and accountability stories. "We caught our own overclaims" is a rare story — most AI companies do not publicize their internal correction process. The verify-net is a genuine institutional discipline, not a marketing frame. This piece builds trust before the Tier 3 benchmark lands.

**Gate:** Requires honest accounting of what was caught and corrected. Cannot be a puff piece. The catches must be named by type and date.

